<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="281" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,151,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[328,500,151,176]" class="Demospongiae" family="Raspailiidae" genus="Eurypon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="distyli" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[328,500,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">Eurypon distyli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[508,598,151,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[508,598,151,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is the only 
<taxonomicName box="[731,827,153,176]" class="Demospongiae" family="Raspailiidae" genus="Eurypon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[731,827,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">Eurypon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Atlantic with two categories of styles and large raphides.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,560,223,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
External morphology (
<figureCitation box="[473,545,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1193,1215]" captionTargetBox="[201,1385,394,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[198,1389,393,1171]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, fresh holotype taken out of the water, showing spicules; B, details of the surface; C, basal layer of spongin with echinating acanthostyles. Scale bars: A = 1 cm; B = 200 µm; C = 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225596/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[530,545,223,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Encrusting sponge, covering surfaces up to 
<quantity box="[1069,1126,223,248]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" unit="cm" value="2.0">2 cm</quantity>
<number box="[1126,1135,223,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="2.0">²</number>
diameter and 
<quantity box="[1300,1436,223,248]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" unit="mm" value="1.0" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.5">0.5–1.5 mm</quantity>
thick, growing over rocks (
<figureCitation box="[475,548,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1193,1215]" captionTargetBox="[201,1385,394,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[198,1389,393,1171]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, fresh holotype taken out of the water, showing spicules; B, details of the surface; C, basal layer of spongin with echinating acanthostyles. Scale bars: A = 1 cm; B = 200 µm; C = 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225596/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[533,548,260,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Oscules not visible. Surface hispid due to evenly distributed projecting spicules and with some bouquets of spicules irregularly distributed (
<figureCitation box="[911,978,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1193,1215]" captionTargetBox="[201,1385,394,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[198,1389,393,1171]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, fresh holotype taken out of the water, showing spicules; B, details of the surface; C, basal layer of spongin with echinating acanthostyles. Scale bars: A = 1 cm; B = 200 µm; C = 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225596/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[963,978,295,320]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Consistency firm and difficult to tear. Color in life is green, dark green in ethanol.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225596/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" targetBox="[201,1385,394,1170]" targetPageId="8">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1193,1276]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1193,1215]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">FIGURE 6.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[282,438,1193,1215]" class="Demospongiae" family="Raspailiidae" genus="Eurypon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="distyli" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[282,438,1193,1215]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">Eurypon distyli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[445,526,1193,1214]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[445,526,1193,1214]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, fresh holotype taken out of the water, showing spicules; B, details of the surface; C, basal layer of spongin with echinating acanthostyles. Scale bars: A = 1 cm; B = 200 µm; C = 100 µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1315,2024]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,416,1315,1340]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Skeleton (
<figureCitation box="[324,401,1315,1340]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1193,1215]" captionTargetBox="[201,1385,394,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[198,1389,393,1171]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, fresh holotype taken out of the water, showing spicules; B, details of the surface; C, basal layer of spongin with echinating acanthostyles. Scale bars: A = 1 cm; B = 200 µm; C = 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225596/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[386,401,1315,1340]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
The ectosomal skeleton is absent, with tips of choanosomal the spicules externally protruding (
<figureCitation box="[286,355,1351,1376]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1193,1215]" captionTargetBox="[201,1385,394,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[198,1389,393,1171]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, fresh holotype taken out of the water, showing spicules; B, details of the surface; C, basal layer of spongin with echinating acanthostyles. Scale bars: A = 1 cm; B = 200 µm; C = 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225596/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[340,355,1351,1376]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
B). The choanosomal skeleton is a hymedesmioid structure with a basal layer of acanthostyles, auxiliary styles and principal subtylostyles, are all perpendicular to the substrate (
<figureCitation box="[1172,1248,1387,1412]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1193,1215]" captionTargetBox="[201,1385,394,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[198,1389,393,1171]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, fresh holotype taken out of the water, showing spicules; B, details of the surface; C, basal layer of spongin with echinating acanthostyles. Scale bars: A = 1 cm; B = 200 µm; C = 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225596/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[1234,1248,1387,1412]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
B and C). The subectosomal styles I and II are dispersed in the subectosomal region of the erect spicule skeleton.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1315,2024]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,946,1459,1484]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Spicules (
<figureCitation box="[314,385,1459,1484]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spicule composition of Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, subtylostyle; B, style I; C, style II; D, raphide; E, acanthostyle; F, details of the flattened spines; G, details of the base of A; H, details of the base of B; I, details of the base of C. Scale bars: A = 200 µm; B = 40 µm; C = 50 µm; D = 30 µm; E, G, H = 10 µm; F = 5 µm; I = 3 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225598/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[371,385,1459,1484]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
A–I). Choanosomal subtylostyles (
<figureCitation box="[798,869,1459,1484]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spicule composition of Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, subtylostyle; B, style I; C, style II; D, raphide; E, acanthostyle; F, details of the flattened spines; G, details of the base of A; H, details of the base of B; I, details of the base of C. Scale bars: A = 200 µm; B = 40 µm; C = 50 µm; D = 30 µm; E, G, H = 10 µm; F = 5 µm; I = 3 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225598/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[855,869,1459,1484]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
A, G):
</emphasis>
long, smooth, slender, slightly curved and with bulbous base (
<number box="[371,499,1495,1520]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="1935.0" valueMax="2810.0" valueMin="1060.0">1060–2810</number>
/ 
<number box="[522,578,1496,1520]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="12.5" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="7.0">7–18</number>
µm); 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[649,1065,1495,1520]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Subectosomal styles I (
<figureCitation box="[922,992,1495,1520]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spicule composition of Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, subtylostyle; B, style I; C, style II; D, raphide; E, acanthostyle; F, details of the flattened spines; G, details of the base of A; H, details of the base of B; I, details of the base of C. Scale bars: A = 200 µm; B = 40 µm; C = 50 µm; D = 30 µm; E, G, H = 10 µm; F = 5 µm; I = 3 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225598/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[977,992,1495,1520]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
B, H):
</emphasis>
smooth, lightly robust and often straight (
<number box="[254,354,1531,1556]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="400.0" valueMax="485.0" valueMin="315.0">315–485</number>
/ 
<number box="[385,426,1531,1556]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="6.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="5.0">5–7</number>
µm); 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[505,1064,1531,1556]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Subectosomal style II (anisoxea) (
<figureCitation box="[923,996,1531,1556]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spicule composition of Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, subtylostyle; B, style I; C, style II; D, raphide; E, acanthostyle; F, details of the flattened spines; G, details of the base of A; H, details of the base of B; I, details of the base of C. Scale bars: A = 200 µm; B = 40 µm; C = 50 µm; D = 30 µm; E, G, H = 10 µm; F = 5 µm; I = 3 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225598/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[981,996,1531,1556]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
C, I):
</emphasis>
smooth, thin and varying from straight to curved (
<number box="[377,476,1567,1592]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="376.0" valueMax="437.0" valueMin="315.0">315–437</number>
/ 
<number box="[508,571,1567,1592]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="3.75" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="3.0">3–4.5</number>
µm); 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[651,895,1567,1592]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Raphides (
<figureCitation box="[783,857,1567,1592]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spicule composition of Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, subtylostyle; B, style I; C, style II; D, raphide; E, acanthostyle; F, details of the flattened spines; G, details of the base of A; H, details of the base of B; I, details of the base of C. Scale bars: A = 200 µm; B = 40 µm; C = 50 µm; D = 30 µm; E, G, H = 10 µm; F = 5 µm; I = 3 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225598/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[842,857,1567,1592]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
D):
</emphasis>
usually straight, smooth and with sharp ends (
<number box="[159,258,1604,1628]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="246.5" valueMax="372.0" valueMin="121.0">121–372</number>
/ less than 
<number box="[393,428,1603,1628]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="0.5">0.5</number>
µm); 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[501,824,1603,1628]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Acanthostyles (
<figureCitation box="[685,755,1603,1628]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spicule composition of Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, subtylostyle; B, style I; C, style II; D, raphide; E, acanthostyle; F, details of the flattened spines; G, details of the base of A; H, details of the base of B; I, details of the base of C. Scale bars: A = 200 µm; B = 40 µm; C = 50 µm; D = 30 µm; E, G, H = 10 µm; F = 5 µm; I = 3 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225598/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[741,755,1603,1628]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
E–F):
</emphasis>
usually straight, fusiform, with base slightly bulbous and surface completely spined. The spines are short and curved (
<number box="[875,961,1639,1664]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="98.0" valueMax="129.0" valueMin="67.0">67–129</number>
µm long), at the base the spines are hookshaped and in the middle region the spines are spatulate 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[782,927,1675,1700]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
(see 
<figureCitation box="[834,901,1675,1700]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1486,1508]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,179,1464]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spicule composition of Eurypon distyli sp. nov. (UFPEPOR 1601, holotype). A, subtylostyle; B, style I; C, style II; D, raphide; E, acanthostyle; F, details of the flattened spines; G, details of the base of A; H, details of the base of B; I, details of the base of C. Scale bars: A = 200 µm; B = 40 µm; C = 50 µm; D = 30 µm; E, G, H = 10 µm; F = 5 µm; I = 3 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/225598/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="281">
Fig. 
<number box="[887,901,1675,1700]" pageId="8" pageNumber="281" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
F)
</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
